        <div class="container">
   			<table style='border: 0; width: 100%; table-layout: fixed' id='blogTable' class='wsite-not-footer'><tr><td valign='top'><div id='634459056234228342-blog' class='blog-body' style='float: left;'>
<div id="wsite-content">	<div id="blog-post-475767354544631062" class="blog-post">
	
	
		<div class="blog-header">
			<h2 class="blog-title">
					<a class="blog-title-link blog-link" href="//edtech541schafer.weebly.com/blog/taking-drill-and-kill-to-drill-for-skill">Taking  "Drill and Kill"  to  "Drill For Skill"</a>

			</h2>
			<p class="blog-date">
					<span class="date-text">
		2/16/2014
	</span>

			</p>
			<p class="blog-comments">
					<a href="//edtech541schafer.weebly.com/blog/taking-drill-and-kill-to-drill-for-skill#comments" class="blog-link">
		4 Comments
	</a>

			</p>
		</div>
	
		<div class="blog-separator">&nbsp;</div>
	
		<div class="blog-content">
				<div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-thin " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a> <img src="/uploads/2/0/1/3/20135489/3863198_orig.gif" alt="Picture" style="width:100%;max-width:650px" /> </a> <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div></div>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">Teachers have an almost universal and automatic response to the scene above.&nbsp;<br /><br />Let me rephrase that...<br /><br /><br /><strong>Good</strong> teachers have an almost universal and automatic response &nbsp;to the scene above: "That will <strong>never</strong>&nbsp;be me in my classroom".&nbsp;<br /><br />As a result, current teachers have an aversion to anything that resembles a worksheet, a drill and practice activity, or a pre-test. Years of abuse of the worksheet, and drill and practice activities in general, have led to the &nbsp;term "drill and kill". Somehow, we equate practicing a skill to killing the creativity and enthusiasm for a subject within the learner. Educators have stories much like the comic above to add fuel to the attitudes towards the subject. During my first three years of teaching, I worked with a teacher who would hand out word search puzzles/worksheets and play episodes of the t.v. show House for his health courses. Every class, everyday, all year long. I often imagine his reaction to a copy machine apocalypse.<br /><br />Current trends in education like PBL (both Problem-based and Project-based Learning), collaborative learning, experiential learning, and lab-based educational models have replaced the much more "traditional" model of lecture/explanation/demonstration and then practice or drill. I work in a school where Project-Based Learning is the focus. It is a great environment in which most students are pushed far beyond even their own expectations, producing end deliverables and products that are professional, thorough, and show a deep understanding of the content area. But I wonder, what do we do with the students who lack the most basic skills in a subject area when those skills are necessary for the completion of a collaborative project? If left unaddressed, the student will withdraw from the group work and rely heavily on the other team members to pick up the slack. Could it be that well-placed, drill and practice activities would result in improved skill acquisition among students who struggle with basic concepts?<br /><br />Drill and practice software is inexpensive and available for most subject areas and could be the answer to the question above (Crowe, 1996). In fact,<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; "two large-scale, longitudinal studies that spanned the 1990s along with findings&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; from several meta-analyses between 1985 and 2000 show impressive student&nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; gains resulting from drill and practice software use." &nbsp;<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; (Ringstaff &amp; Kelley, 2002)<br /><br />When a student need is identified, the teacher should determine whether a drill and skill software activity could help solidify skills needed before the student moves on. It is a lot like taking music lessons from a private instructor. The instructor works with the musician to determine skill deficits and exercises to help with those skills before the musician moves on to more difficult concepts. Drill until the skill is demonstrated and then move on. It is a shift from the educator's mindset of "drill and kill" to "drill to skill". &nbsp;Educators can identify student needs that "drills can meet and use software in ways that take advantage of its capabilities" (Roblyer &amp; Doering, 2013, p85).&nbsp;<br /><br />I have compiled a list of resources below for performing arts teachers.Click the links below for examples of both free and paid software programs that will give you some really good "drill to skill" tools for use in the classroom.<br /><br /></div>  <div><div class="wsite-multicol"><div class='wsite-multicol-table-wrap' style='margin:0 -15px'> <table class='wsite-multicol-table'> <tbody class='wsite-multicol-tbody'> <tr class='wsite-multicol-tr'> <td class='wsite-multicol-col' style='width:50%;padding:0 15px'>  <div style="text-align:left;"><div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div> <a class="wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal" href="http://www.shmoop.com/julius-caesar/flashcards.html" target="_blank"> <span class="wsite-button-inner">SHMOOP - Shakespeare</span> </a> <div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div></div>  <div style="text-align:left;"><div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div> <a class="wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal" href="http://www.finalemusic.com/" target="_blank"> <span class="wsite-button-inner">Finale</span> </a> <div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div></div>  </td> <td class='wsite-multicol-col' style='width:50%;padding:0 15px'>  <div style="text-align:left;"><div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div> <a class="wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal" href="http://www.musictheory.net/exercises/note" target="_blank"> <span class="wsite-button-inner">Note Identification</span> </a> <div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div></div>  <div style="text-align:left;"><div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div> <a class="wsite-button wsite-button-small wsite-button-normal" href="http://www.musictheory.net/exercises/ear-interval" target="_blank"> <span class="wsite-button-inner">Musical Intervals</span> </a> <div style="height: 10px; overflow: hidden;"></div></div>  </td> </tr> </tbody> </table> </div></div></div>  <h2 class="wsite-content-title" style="text-align:left;"><font size="5">Resources</font></h2>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;">Roblyer, M.D., &amp; Doering, A.H. (2013). <em>Integrating Educational Technology into Teaching</em> (6th ed.). Upper Saddle &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; River, NJ: Pearson Education, Inc.<br /><br />Crowe, J.A. (1996). <em>Using Technology in Education</em>. retrieved from &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; www.robles.callutheran.edu/~crowe/software.html<br /><br />Ringstaff, C., &amp; Kelley, L. (2002). <em>The Learning Return on Our Educational Technology Investment: A Review of &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Findings from Research</em>. Wested Policy Brief. retrieved from &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; http://www.wested.org/online_pubs/po-02-01/</div>

		</div>
	
	
