				<div class="blogCommentText">
					<p>
							I found your blog post interesting because of your view as a performing arts teacher working in a PBL school.  Not only are drill and practice activities inexpensive and available for most subject areas (as you state), students can work independently to gain more practice and acquire knowledge.  They can work at their own pace and repeat activities as necessary.  I believe drill and practice activities are an asset in any type of instruction and would work well in a performing arts setting.<br/>
<br/>
I was hoping to see your assignment to find out your views on the other four areas of instructional software.  I wondered what performing arts resources you would share for those areas.  <br/>
<br/>
Coming from a traditional school and teaching one grade level with many topics, I appreciated the views you shared on how to use drill and practice in your setting.
