I like the cartoon at the beginning of the post; nice touch of creativity!<br/>
<br/>
It also makes a very good point, and strikes home the notion that educators can either use a tool correctly, or incorrectly. It is easy to lean on "worksheets" or have the math software running for the duration of the class, but as your post points out, teachers need to identify their students and pick the right tools.<br/>
<br/>
I actually was going to do some more research on drill-and-practice options, so your resources above saved me some time! I am guessing that is what works best in your field. With performing arts, I am betting it can be really useful in achieving some of your objectives. The note flashcard above I see a being really helpful. The ear training is a tool that I suppose I knew existed, but never gave it thought. Wow, a music student these days has many tools they can use! I wonder your thoughts on how technology is impacting students in your field; are the developing faster, becoming better, etc.<br/>

